The busy plot on the right shows
the summary of the contributions

97
00:06:55,560 --> 00:06:58,960
of all processes to the photon
total cross section in metal.

98
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:05,760
Among this the most important ones are the
photoelectric effect at low energies and

99
00:07:05,760 --> 00:07:07,630
pair production at high energies

100
00:07:08,820 --> 00:07:13,140
In between around 1 MeV, at
the minimum of the cross section,

101
00:07:13,140 --> 00:07:15,800
Compton scattering dominates
over other processes.

102
00:07:18,750 --> 00:07:23,180
At high energy, as we have seen at
energies above 1 GeV, electrons and

103
00:07:23,180 --> 00:07:27,370
positrons lose their energy almost
exclusively by bremsstrahlung.

104
00:07:27,370 --> 00:07:31,570
Photons convert to electrons and
positrons by pair production.

105
00:07:31,570 --> 00:07:34,400
The two phenomena have the same
characteristic length,

106
00:07:34,400 --> 00:07:36,130
the radiation length.

107
00:07:36,130 --> 00:07:39,090
The successive combination
of these two effects

108
00:07:39,090 --> 00:07:43,440
results in the formation of what is
called an electromagnetic shower.

109
00:07:43,440 --> 00:07:44,900
Whenever an electron,

110
00:07:44,900 --> 00:07:47,860
positron or photon of high
energy enters into a medium,

111
00:07:47,860 --> 00:07:49,750
it will cause such a shower.

112
